                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You say you died a lot at first and learned some hard lessons.  I've known for awhile now that I'd either need a guide like this or I'd have to do exactly that.
<br />

<br />
In regular LDoN I can be puller, slower, CC, and charming at the same time, and a druid healer is fine.  It's obvious that hard mode means giving up most of that, esp. since I've heard that Pacification is often resisted (a detail strangely missing in your guide).  But other details you must have figured out the hard way.
<br />

<br />
You say that gear does not make the character, you have to be good.  I agree... but to be good you have to know where the margins are, what you can get away with.  For that, I need to know the same lessons you got from all your deaths... why/when were you dying and what did you change because of it?  That's the info I need for good threat analysis and split second decisions.  Even if your style matched my style completely, I'd still need to be able to make small adjustments to your (very good) guide based on the group I'm with.
<br />

<br />
Were you dying because you tried to pull?  Or because you hasted your pet and it chewed you up?  Maybe you tried to do slow and CC at the same time and either ran low on mana or suffered some dead clerics.  Or maybe you just learned that rune was more important than root.  Did you have different problems with a paladin puller than with a monk puller?  Does it help to have an evaccer with an itchy trigger finger?
<br />

<br />
If you have that second rune up for those fun CC moments, not just charm breaks... hmm.  Maybe that druid you felt sorry for knows how to snare, kite, and root park adds well enough to do it in a dungeon.  Or maybe your tank is smart enough to back up after one of the adds is rooted (many aren't).  That could make a huge difference on a four-pull.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Sylphan on Sat Jan 03, 2004 5:26 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
