                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Good advice overall, I just wanted to offer a different perspective on this:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Pulling in LDoN High Risk: 
<br />

<br />
Dont do it. In normal risk you can slow pull mez and charm np. This is NOT the case in high risk. Pacification is resisted a LOT more in high risk. With 260 cha its common to get aggro from pacify, with 305 you are pretty much safe from aggro but pacify will still drain your mana fast with all the resists. Even now with over 6k hps I dont mess around with pulling. Occasionally I will have to break up a room with pacify, but this should be your groups back up plan. Pacify is a tool, not a crutch. 
<br />

<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Imo enchanters are potentially the BEST puller there is in ldon hard, reguardless of HP. This is how I pull hard ldon ( this assumes you already have a pet, otherwise, I would let someone else do it if you do not have much hp). For sake of arguement, assume there are at least 2 mobs in each room, otherwise pulling wouldn't be a big deal=P
<br />

<br />
There are really 2 methods you can use, both have essentially the same premise: 
<br />

<br />
* NOTE * neither will work well in EF because pets are casters.
<br />

<br />
1. Tash / Pet method. I find this method best for fewer pulls ( 2/3 mobs). All you have to do is tash one of the mobs in the room and throw your pet on it before they reach close to camp ( in same room is fine, you just want them out of melee range ). The mob you tash will rush toward you, and the other adds will stick on your pet ( they assist the mob you tashed when it gets attacked by the pet). Take care of the mob on you ( root / mezz / stun whichever you prefer). Remember, its already tashed, so spells are pretty likely to stick. From there /assist you pet, tash and mezz. You will NOT outagro your pet. 
<br />

<br />
2. Pet rush method. This works best on rooms of 4+ mobs. Just send you pet in on one of them. When it attacks the rest of the room will rush it. From there, just /assist pet and tash mezz.
<br />

<br />
For the most part, the enchanter stays out of harms way.
<br />

<br />
Pros:
<br />
1. Mobs can be pulled quickly, in chain fashon without a lot of risk.
<br />
2. Mobs can be crowd controlled without agro as long as the enchanter is assisting the pet when tash/mezzing.
<br />
3. You don't have to spam click to find the active target when CCing, just /assist the pet.  ( This saves precious time and resources)
<br />
4. Eliminates much of the "opps.. to many" problems.
<br />

<br />
Cons:
<br />
1. Charm can break post pull. Always a risk.
<br />

<br />
Things to look out for/inform group of so they don't do it:
<br />

<br />
1. Healing the pet while pulling. This will result in every mob the pet doesn't have agro on gang rushing whoever healed it, much like if a healer heals any other class during the "inc" stage of pulling.
<br />

<br />
2. To many people on agro list. Remember, 3 people is the max a mob can have agro on before the pet cannot hold agro. ( The 4th person will force the pet to lose agro). Ideally, the 3 that will be on agro are 1. You the enchanter, 2. The shaman for slowing, and 3. The cleric will likely have a tiny bit of agro from healing you during pull. The agro transfere only seems to happen to the mob the pet is currently on for heal agro, however, so don't be overly concerned.
<br />

<br />
3. Getting to close to camp. If you're in melee range, the mobs wont attack the pet. Don't let that happen.
<br />

<br />
Finally, I won't deny a learning curve. You might die a few times, but hey, learning how to overcome that is what MAKES you a good enchanter. There is natural talent, sure, but without taking the time to aquire new skills, its useless. 
<br />

<br />
So what can be done to soften the learning curve? Practice it in normal ldon! There is little risk there, and the same theory works on pulling. Once you get good at it there, hard should just seem like more of the same. 
<br />

<br />
Or
<br />

<br />
Jump right into hard. Sometimes diving head first into icy water is the best way to take it.
<br />

<br />
Finally to wrap things up and give some perspective, here is a bit of additional information that may or may not help:
<br />

<br />
-The most i've pulled with these methods is 7 + 1 tashed ( 8 total). Pet started around 80% hp, was at about 15% by the time the last was mezzed.
<br />

<br />
-The method won't be a walk in the park on your mana pool, you will need ST. The tradeoff is less healing mana is used. If you're going lom , don't be afraid to ask the shaman to root some things, the root/push aa they have is extremely helpful.
<br />

<br />
-My spell line up is:
<br />

<br />
Color cloud
<br />
Root
<br />
Insanity
<br />
Archane Rune
<br />
CoD
<br />
Sleep
<br />
Tash
<br />
ST
<br />

<br />
Its a start, but you may need to cusomize yours to your playstyle, or that of your groups. I might suggesting substituting a nuke for zeb or morell.
<br />

<br />
- Don't be afraid to try new things!! =D</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Desseray Lokheart &lt;Frayed Knot&gt;
<br />
65 Coercer - The Rathe
<br />
<img src="http://www.shocking.com/~kestra/pix/des2.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
